“Something went wrong” is not error handling. It’s error avoidance.

ShopFlow’s architecture is now complete — from component to aggregate to API, every layer in place. But there’s one concern that threads through all of them and deserves its own treatment: error handling.
Look at the most common pattern in Angular codebases:
this.http.post('/api/cart/checkout', payload).pipe(
catchError(() => {
this.toast.show('Something went wrong. Please try again.');
return EMPTY;
})
);And the slightly more ambitious version:
catchError((err: HttpErrorResponse) => {
if (err.status === 400) this.errorMessage = err.error?.message ?? 'Bad request';
else if (err.status === 409) this.errorMessage = 'Conflict error';
else this.errorMessage = 'Unknown error';
return EMPTY;
})Both treat every failure as the same kind of problem. But when ShopFlow’s checkout fails, it could be because:

• The coupon expired — a domain error. The business said no.

• The payment processor is down — an application error. Infrastructure failed.

• The postcode field is missing — a validation error. The user made a mistake.

• A null reference exploded in a component — a system error. A bug.
These require completely different handling. Domain errors belong inline, near the action that caused them. Infrastructure errors deserve a retry-able banner. Validation errors belong on the form field. Bugs go to Sentry.
When you handle them identically, users get “something went wrong” for a coupon that expired three days ago.

The Error Hierarchy
The foundation is a typed class hierarchy. Each type of failure gets its own class.
// shared-kernel/errors/domain-error.ts
/**
* A business rule violation. The user did something the domain doesn't allow.
* Always user-actionable - they can change their action.
*/
export abstract class DomainError extends Error {
abstract readonly code: string;
constructor(message: string) {
super(message);
this.name = this.constructor.name;
Object.setPrototypeOf(this, new.target.prototype);
}
}
/**
* An infrastructure or integration failure.
* May be recoverable with a retry.
*/
export abstract class ApplicationError extends Error {
abstract readonly code: string;
constructor(message: string) {
super(message);
this.name = this.constructor.name;
Object.setPrototypeOf(this, new.target.prototype);
}
}Cart and Checkout Domain Errors
// cart/domain/errors/cart.errors.ts
export class CartIsEmptyError extends DomainError {
readonly code = 'CART_IS_EMPTY';
constructor() { super('Your cart is empty. Add items before checking out.'); }
}
export class CartAlreadyCheckedOutError extends DomainError {
readonly code = 'CART_ALREADY_CHECKED_OUT';
constructor() { super('This cart has already been checked out.'); }
}
export class CartItemQuantityExceededError extends DomainError {
readonly code = 'CART_ITEM_QUANTITY_EXCEEDED';
constructor(readonly productName: string, readonly max: number) {
super(`You can only add up to ${max} of "${productName}" per order.`);
}
}
export class CouponAlreadyAppliedError extends DomainError {
readonly code = 'COUPON_ALREADY_APPLIED';
constructor(readonly appliedCode: string) {
super(`Coupon "${appliedCode}" is already applied. Remove it first.`);
}
}
export class CouponExpiredError extends DomainError {
readonly code = 'COUPON_EXPIRED';
constructor(readonly couponCode: string, readonly expiredAt: Date) {
super(`Coupon "${couponCode}" expired on ${expiredAt.toLocaleDateString()}.`);
}
}
export class CouponMinimumNotMetError extends DomainError {
readonly code = 'COUPON_MINIMUM_NOT_MET';
constructor(readonly couponCode: string, readonly minimumAmount: string) {
super(`Coupon "${couponCode}" requires a minimum order of ${minimumAmount}.`);
}
}
export class ProductOutOfStockError extends DomainError {
readonly code = 'PRODUCT_OUT_OF_STOCK';
constructor(readonly productName: string) {
super(`"${productName}" is currently out of stock.`);
}
}// checkout/domain/errors/checkout.errors.ts
export class PaymentDeclinedError extends DomainError {
readonly code = 'PAYMENT_DECLINED';
constructor(readonly reason: 'insufficient_funds' | 'card_expired' | 'do_not_honour' | 'unknown') {
const messages = {
insufficient_funds: 'Your payment was declined - insufficient funds.',
card_expired: 'Your card has expired. Please use a different card.',
do_not_honour: 'Your bank declined this payment. Please contact your bank.',
unknown: 'Your payment was declined. Please try a different payment method.',
};
super(messages[reason]);
}
}
export class AddressNotDeliverableError extends DomainError {
readonly code = 'ADDRESS_NOT_DELIVERABLE';
constructor(readonly postcode: string) {
super(`We don't deliver to postcode ${postcode} yet.`);
}
}Application Errors
// shared-kernel/errors/application.errors.ts
export class NetworkUnavailableError extends ApplicationError {
readonly code = 'NETWORK_UNAVAILABLE';
constructor() { super('No internet connection. Please check your network and try again.'); }
}
export class ServiceUnavailableError extends ApplicationError {
readonly code = 'SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE';
constructor(readonly serviceName: string) {
super(`${serviceName} is temporarily unavailable. Please try again in a moment.`);
}
}
export class SessionExpiredError extends ApplicationError {
readonly code = 'SESSION_EXPIRED';
constructor() { super('Your session has expired. Please sign in again.'); }
}
export class UnexpectedError extends ApplicationError {
readonly code = 'UNEXPECTED_ERROR';
constructor(readonly originalError?: unknown) {
super('An unexpected error occurred. Our team has been notified.');
}
}
Translating HTTP Errors Into Domain Errors
Raw HttpErrorResponse objects need translation — exactly like DTOs need the mapper:
// shared-kernel/errors/http-error.mapper.ts
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class HttpErrorMapper {
toDomainError(err: HttpErrorResponse): DomainError | ApplicationError {
if (err.status === 0) return new NetworkUnavailableError();
if (err.status === 401) return new SessionExpiredError();
if (err.status === 503 || err.status === 502) return new ServiceUnavailableError('ShopFlow');
if (err.status === 422 || err.status === 409 || err.status === 400) {
return this.mapApiDomainError(err.error);
}
return new UnexpectedError(err);
}
private mapApiDomainError(body: ApiErrorBody): DomainError | ApplicationError {
if (!body?.error_code) return new UnexpectedError(body);
switch (body.error_code) {
case 'CART_IS_EMPTY':
return new CartIsEmptyError();
case 'CART_ITEM_QUANTITY_EXCEEDED':
return new CartItemQuantityExceededError(
body.details?.product_name ?? 'this product',
body.details?.max_quantity ?? 10,
);
case 'COUPON_EXPIRED':
return new CouponExpiredError(
body.details?.coupon_code ?? '',
new Date(body.details?.expired_at ?? Date.now()),
);
case 'PAYMENT_DECLINED':
return new PaymentDeclinedError(body.details?.reason ?? 'unknown');
default:
return new UnexpectedError(body);
}
}
}When the backend sends a 422 with error_code: 'COUPON_EXPIRED', the mapper produces a CouponExpiredError with the expiry date already formatted in its message. The component just displays error.message. No status code inspection. No string parsing.

Result<T, E>: Errors as Values
Throwing errors breaks RxJS chains in unexpected ways and forces try/catch in places that shouldn’t need it. A Result type makes errors first-class values — typed, explicit, and handled at the call site.
// shared-kernel/result.ts
export type Result<T, E extends Error = Error> =
| { success: true; value: T }
| { success: false; error: E };
export const Result = {
ok<T>(value: T): Result<T, never> { return { success: true, value }; },
fail<E extends Error>(error: E): Result<never, E> { return { success: false, error }; },
};In the Component
The component displays error.message. No switch statements on status codes. No HTTP knowledge:
@Component({
selector: 'shopflow-coupon-field',
standalone: true,
template: `
<div class="coupon-field">
<input [(ngModel)]="couponCode" placeholder="Discount code" />
<button (click)="apply()" [disabled]="applying()">
{{ applying() ? 'Applying…' : 'Apply' }}
</button>
@if (errorMessage()) { <p class="error">{{ errorMessage() }}</p> }
@if (successMessage()) { <p class="success">{{ successMessage() }}</p> }
</div>
`
})
export class CouponFieldComponent {
couponCode = '';
readonly applying = signal(false);
readonly errorMessage = signal<string | null>(null);
readonly successMessage = signal<string | null>(null);
private cartFacade = inject(CartFacade);
apply(): void {
this.applying.set(true);
this.errorMessage.set(null);
this.cartFacade.applyCoupon(this.couponCode).subscribe(result => {
this.applying.set(false);
if (result.success) {
this.successMessage.set('Coupon applied!');
this.couponCode = '';
return;
}
// The domain error already carries the right message
this.errorMessage.set(result.error.message);
});
}
}
NgRx: Typed Errors in State
Store errors as typed plain objects, then use selectors to distinguish domain errors from system errors:
export interface CartError {
code: string;
message: string;
type: 'domain' | 'application' | 'unexpected';
}// Domain error: the user can act on it
export const selectCartDomainError = createSelector(
selectCartState,
state => state.error?.type === 'domain' ? state.error : null
);
// System error: show a retry-able banner
export const selectCartSystemError = createSelector(
selectCartState,
state => state.error?.type !== 'domain' ? state.error : null
);
@if (domainError$ | async; as err) {
<p class="inline-error">{{ err.message }}</p>
}
@if (systemError$ | async) {
<div class="banner-error">
Something went wrong on our end.
<button (click)="retry()">Try again</button>
</div>
}

Which Error Goes Where
Error occurred
│
├─ Business rule violation?
│ (coupon expired, out of stock, payment declined)
│ → DomainError → show inline, near the action → user can fix it
│
├─ User input missing or malformed?
│ → ValidationError → show on the form field
│
├─ Network or service failure?
│ → ApplicationError → retry-able banner → not the user's fault
│
├─ Session expired?
│ → SessionExpiredError → redirect to login
│
└─ Bug?
→ UnexpectedError → log to monitoring → generic message to user
Key Takeaways
Typed domain errors are unambiguous. CouponExpiredError is completely clear. err.status === 422 is not.
Each error type carries a user-ready message. The component just displays it — no message mapping in the UI layer.
The Result<T, E> type makes error handling explicit in method signatures. No unchecked exceptions escaping into unexpected places.
NgRx state typed with CartError lets selectors distinguish user-actionable domain errors from system-level failures — so you can show them differently in the template.

What’s Next
We’ve treated errors as a first-class domain concern. The last article covers the Shared Kernel in depth — the one place every context imports from, and the easiest place for the old SharedModule problem to quietly re-emerge.

